AB  - Learned PublishingVolume 31, Issue 4 p. 331-333 EditorialFree Access A sting in the tail? Pippa Smart, Pippa Smart Editor-in-Chief, Learned Publishing editor@alpsp.org orcid.org/0000-0002-5528-4704 Search for more papers by this author Pippa Smart, Pippa Smart Editor-in-Chief, Learned Publishing editor@alpsp.org orcid.org/0000-0002-5528-4704 Search for more papers by this author First published: 04 October 2018 https://doi.org/10.1002/leap.1202Citations: 2AboutSectionsPDF ToolsRequest permissionExport citationAdd to favoritesTrack citation ShareShare Give accessShare full text accessShare full-text accessPlease review our Terms and Conditions of Use and check box below to share full-text version of article.I have read and accept the Wiley Online Library Terms and Conditions of UseShareable LinkUse the link below to share a full-text version of this article with your friends and colleagues. Learn more.Copy URL Share a linkShare onFacebookTwitterLinkedInRedditWechat Can we no longer trust what is published? Last month I was caught up in a 'sting' to identify predatory journals. I had reviewed an article for a journal and after submitting my review (with recommendation of Reject) I came across the same article in a leading journal/magazine. As the article sent to me had been blinded, I assumed that the authors had plagiarized the article. However, it had been submitted by the same author group and the journal editors (who had also identified the duplication) started pursuing the matter with the authors. A few weeks later the lead author contacted the journal to say he was withdrawing it and he revealed that it had been part of an ethics committee approved research project in which the same article had been sent to 600 journals to see if they would spot that it was already published. Like many other people, I have read the several stings that test dodgy journals (e.g. Bohannon, 2013) with interest and been shocked to discover how apparently bad their quality control systems are. However, being the recipient gave me a somewhat different perspective. I had spent a few precious hours reviewing an article for no purpose and I have to admit that I was annoyed about the waste of time – as were the journal editors. The journal it had been submitted to cannot afford the time or money to check every submission via a reliable duplication-checking tool, and I suspect many of the other journals participating in the research were in a similar situation. On the one hand, it will be interesting to discover how many journals accepted the article without discovering its duplication, and on the other hand, it is concerning that so many precious reviewer-hours have been lost to reviewing this article. At Learned Publishing, we do not routinely check every article for plagiarism but rely on the integrity of the authors – only checking where we have a suspicion (style changes or other hints). Our decision is informed by experience, and in the past few years we have only once found a true case of plagiarism – all other apparent duplications were legitimate. The premise behind the research project above, however, is that authors cannot be trusted and all editors should be checking everything. The questions over scholarly trust and integrity continue to make headline news. Concerns about 'fake news' in scholarly publishing either from fraudulent authors or poor quality journals have reached the mainstream press outlets. There is understandable concern about the trustworthiness of scholarly information. An article in the Indian Express ('pay, publish, profit' Yadav, 2018) outlines an emerging industry in low quality journals, which have arisen to provide an outlet for the booming number of researchers and the increasing pressure to publish. Several German journalists initiated their own sting by submitting an article on the use of propolis to control cancer. The rubbish article was both accepted and published, although it has now been retracted. (The article can be found at the following URL: https://www.omicsonline.org/peer-reviewed/combined-effects-of-ethylacetate-extracts-of-propolis-inducing-cell-death-of-human-colorectal-adenocarcinoma-cells-102225.html.) (I am not citing it as I do not want to 'reward' the journal with citation.) Whilst the sting proved a point about lack of quality controls, it should be remembered that the article remains available and citable in support of other hypotheses and research. Whilst the sting may have proved a point, the journalists are now responsible for yet more untrustworthy research being published. It is of particular note that so many articles in this issue of Learned Publishing cover the subject of trust and reliability from different perspectives. Several articles describe the research publishing environment operating in other regions and provide windows to very different experiences. Mahmood Maniati and Alireza Jalilifar (2018) describe the attitudes and strategies of Iranian authors to achieve publication. Iranian authors are usually required to write in English and often suffer from limited research environments but where expectations of publication are high if they wish to keep their jobs. As the authors reveal, Iranian researchers not only have to rely on enlightened editors who are willing to go the extra mile but often feel obliged to adopt unethical strategies in order to achieve publication in the journals of their choice. The strategies do not – according to the authors – undermine the value of the science that the articles report, but they would fail the 'ethical imperative' that is placed on authorship. From the other side of the fence, Radovan Vrana (2018) discusses the challenges that face editors based in small research communities. His analysis of the problems experienced by Croatian editors demonstrates similar problems as faced by all editors, but exacerbated by their environment. He reports difficulties in obtaining reviewers, poor quality reviewer reports, and author misconduct. Comparing this article with the one from Iran clearly demonstrates the tension between the authors' need to publish and the journal editors' wish to maintain standards and selectivity. It is an invidious problem in any journal, but enhanced in resource-poor environments. Vrana describes the huge difficulty in obtaining good reviewers when journals are seen to be 'peripheral' and lack branding. Without good quality review it is hard (perhaps impossible) to only publish high quality research, and so the journals languish in a mid-quality limbo. Promising support to such journals as Vrana describes, as well as those that may be less reliable (or even fraudulent) is a booming industry of accreditation. The article by Xia and Smith (2018) investigates such services. Journals compete to attract authors as well as improve the likelihood of reviewers accepting invitations to review. To help in this competition, they often look for external validation. The gold standard is indexing within Scopus or Medline, or the achievement of an Impact Factor, but only a small number of journals actually achieve this. The recent problems with the Indian University Grants Commission list of recognized journals show how difficult this process of identifying quality journals can be (Patwardhan et al., 2018). The article from Xia and Smith reports on their investigation into companies who have created different metrics for accrediting journals. They reveal a potentially misleading and even fraudulent accreditation system, but one that is being applied as a proxy for trust (in the same way that the Impact Factor is used). Whether the participating journals are aware or not is unclear; however, the application of these validation tools is certainly misleading to researchers (my own discussions with researchers in Egypt and other countries). A fourth aspect of judging the quality control and relevance of journals is addressed by Camillo Lamanna and Stevan Bruijns (2018). Lamanna and Bruijns question what metrics are really useful for determining journal and article relevance – especially in developing regions. They question the accepted proxy of citations as a meaningful quality measure for all users and propose different methods for developing regions such as the sub-Saharan African countries. They suggest that citations are only valid measures within close networks and question their use for those outside these networks. And finally, the paper by Scott, Gibson, and Benner (2018) reveals how drug advertising in journals is frequently misleading because it lacks suitable supporting references – and frequently cites as evidence works authored by company staff. Their conclusion is that such advertising fails the ethical quality criteria that the journals' editorial systems require. Whilst their investigation does not question the quality of research articles in the journals they evaluated, they do reveal shockingly low standards in the advertising which the selected medical journals carry. This has trust implications for the journal as a whole, since it is reasonable for readers to assume the same integrity levels are applied throughout the journal. The questions of trust and quality are also central to our first review articles. This new article type will review interesting industry white papers and other reports and ensure they are archived for future reference. The first two of these articles by Rachel Kessler (2018) and Tom Hill (2018) review papers on data sharing and blockchain in research, respectively. These two areas are under regular discussion as methods for increasing transparency, reproducibility, and validation of scholarship. Returning to the 'sting' research that led to this editorial. We work on a system of trust in publishing, which (if you believe the frequent publications on the topic) appears to be eroding daily. However the focus of discussions on 'predatory' journals may be a selective bias that ignores other problems of equal concern. Can – and should – we trust authors? Should we no longer trust what is published in journals? Can we believe any of the accreditation systems? Are even the trusted journals allowing unreliable content to be published? And how much should we be concerned about this? I suggest that perhaps the ease of establishing online open journals funded by authors under pressure to publish may be backfiring. There is a rapidly growing research population who need a commensurate growth of journals to accommodate their outputs. Equally, this growing research population needs a reliable system that both educates and rewards them on the quality of their work, rather than demanding output. Unless a means of accrediting published research is identified that encompasses all researchers and all journals – not just the small percentage lucky enough to be included in the key indexes – we will perpetuate the existing landscape that divides elite researchers/readers from the underprivileged. Those that can afford it will pay the high APCs to publish in high quality journals, and those that cannot will turn to other (potentially untrustworthy) journals. Equally, where publishing is dominated by commercial interests this is always going to influence how and what is published. These commercial influences are rarely considered by those looking for scholarly content, but because they could affect what is published they have direct effect on trustworthiness. The leading role for academic institutions cannot be underestimated if we are to avoid disenfranchising large swathes of the research community. Unfortunately, however, the mismatch between the global publishing environment and a fragmented evaluation system will make a solution which is in the public interest hard to find. Biography REFERENCES Bohannon, J. (2013). Who's afraid of peer review? Science, 342(6154), 60– 65. https://doi.org/10.1126/science.342.6154.60 Hill, T. (2018). Blockchain for research: Review. Learned Publishing. https://doi.org/10.1002/leap.1182 Kessler, R. (2018). Whitepaper: Practical challenges for researchers in data sharing: Review. Learned Publishing. https://doi.org/10.1002/leap.1184 Lamanna, C., & Bruijns, S. (2018). Measuring regional impact: The case for bigger data. Learned Publishing. https://doi.org/10.1002/leap.1183 Maniati, M., & Jalilifar, A. (2018). Strategies for publishing in English journals: A study of the perceptions of Iranian scholars. Learned Publishing. https://doi.org/10.1002/leap.1186 Patwardhan, B., Nagarkar, S., Gadre, S. R., Lakhotia, S. C., Katoch, V. M., & Moher, D. (2018). A critical analysis of the 'UGC-approved list of journals. Current Science, 114(06), 1299– 1303. https://doi.org/10.18520/cs/v114/i06/1299-1303 Scott, J. R., Gibson, M., & Benner, R. S. (2018). Contemporary drug advertising in leading US medical journals. Learned Publishing. https://doi.org/10.1002/leap.1189 Vrana, R. (2018). Editorial challenges in a small scientific community: Study of Croatian editors. Learned Publishing. https://doi.org/10.1002/leap.1188 Xia, J., & Smith, M. P. (2018). Alternative journal impact factors in open access publishing. Learned Publishing. Yadav, S. ( 2018, 19 July). Inside India's fake research paper shops: Pay, publish, profit [Web log post]. Retrieved from https://indianexpress.com/article/india/inside-indias-fake-research-paper-shops-pay-publish-profit-5265402/ Citing Literature Volume31, Issue4October 2018Pages 331-333 ReferencesRelatedInformation
