AB  - As an industry, scholarly publishing attracts more women than men. Yet despite their majority, there is a concerning dearth of women in the industry's most senior positions. Furthermore, and we will posit, contributing to this leadership divide, there is a significant gender gap in speaking opportunities at major industry conferences. In this paper, we will present the research that supports these claims and offer three distinct challenges – to publishing organizations; to the women that work for them; and to the community at large – to help address this imbalance and improve gender parity, both at the podium and in the boardroom. In 2014, preparing for a Society for Scholarly Publishing (SSP) panel entitled ‘Mind the Gap—Addressing the Need for More Women Leaders in Scholarly Publishing’, we analysed the then-current SSP roster of 956 individual members. This list revealed a ratio of 58%/42% women to men. Digital Science's recent demographic survey of 828 individuals across 33 countries corroborated this majority, reporting a ratio of 63%/37% women to men (Wheeler, 2015). This likely does not come as a surprise for anyone who has worked for a major scholarly publisher or attended an industry conference. However, it presents an important baseline for this paper's recommendations: parity based on demographics, not on special treatment. In our 2014 analysis, we examined 68 of SSP's organizational members, finding that at that time, only 24% had a female CEO or equivalent, and just 17% (of a partial list of 54 with data publicly available) had a female chairperson or equivalent. For this paper, we expanded our research to a list of 186 ALPSP organizational members. The ALPSP membership was selected as being representative of a wider swathe of scholarly publishers of different size, revenue, region, and market focus. Note that the list, when accessed in October 2015, included 253 organizational members. For this analysis, we excluded individual consultancies, journals, and those for which leadership data was not publicly available. Of these 186 organizations, 32% had a female CEO, and 21% (of a partial list of 168 with data publicly available) had a female chairperson. These results are summarized in Fig. 1. Even equipped with these compelling data, we have found this disparity to be difficult for many to swallow. In the wake of our ‘Mind the Gap’ session and subsequent discussions, many commenters – male and female – were quick to point out notable examples of female leadership in scholarly publishing. Indeed, we the authors both come from organizations (BioOne and ORCID, respectively) with female CEOs. Yet, until the percentage of women in senior leadership roles rises closer to the percentage of women in the industry, our focus needs to be on the rule rather than the exceptions, as notable and impressive as they may be. As with many industries, scholarly publishing has a rich tradition of annual meetings and conferences, often bringing together professionals from around the globe. Participation in these events is critical for professional development, and the chance to speak – especially as a keynote speaker – is highly desirable. CVs commonly carry a ‘presentations’ section, and job postings for senior positions frequently cite a history of speaking engagements and conference participation as key desiderata. Clearly, in scholarly publishing as in other industries, there is a link between professional progress, especially to the industry's most senior positions, and the visibility and caché afforded by public-speaking opportunities. We analysed seven major scholarly publishing conferences held in 2015, looking at speaker gender as well as keynote assignment and single-gender panels (summarized in Figs. 2 and 3). Conferences included in the analysis were: Academic Publishing in Europe (APE); Professional & Scholarly Publishing (PSP); Open Access Scholarly Publishers Association (OASPA); Association of Learned Professional and Society Publishers (ALPSP); International Association of Science, Technical and Medical Publishers (STM); Society for Scholarly Publishing (SSP); and Association of American University Presses (AAUP). Of these seven, only one conference fell in line with industry demographics; of AAUP's 142 speakers, 83 were women (58%). SSP also demonstrated a female majority, with 55% women speakers. The other five organizations ranged from 45% down to 17% women speakers, with APE having the lowest percentage. On average, the seven conferences demonstrated a 63% men to 37% women split. Thus, while there is evidence of some diversification efforts, on average, scholarly publishing conferences are under-representing women on their speaker rosters by nearly 20%. Keynote addresses (applied only to those explicitly labelled as such for the purposes of this exercise) represent the largest inequity. Three conferences examined featured only male keynotes, three had keynotes from both men and women, and one had no keynote address. Overall, there were nearly twice as many male to female keynotes (11 by men and six by women out of a pool of 17). Lastly, we examined the prevalent trending hashtag, #allmalepanels, used on social media to highlight panels featuring only male speakers. Our analysis of these seven conferences yielded 15 instances of all-male panels. Interestingly, all but AAUP had at least one all-male panel. Only SSP and AAUP featured the reverse – six and five all-female panels, respectively. If we, as an industry, believe that conference participation is critical to professional development and access to senior leadership positions, then we must create a system that corrects for the significant gender gap in speaking opportunities. Gender disparity does not happen by accident. Mathematician Greg Martin of the University of British Columbia recently made headlines by proving that it was statistically impossible for a speakers’ lineup at a mathematics conference to include only one woman among 20 – even with a conservative 24% female industry representation (Martin, 2015). Extending this to scholarly publishing, with its 58% female majority, we can safely say that a confluence of male keynotes, all-male panels, and overall female-speaking minorities are not accidental results. However, they are likely also not intentional. Instead, they are the result of a system of unacknowledged biases and the tendency to invite individuals to speak who are visible, vocal, and have presented before. In short, gender disparity – and a lack of diversity more generally – is self-perpetuating. I think there is an awareness about ensuring women are represented because so many women work in the scholarly publishing industry. These same women are proposing, organizing, and selecting panelists for sessions. In fact, women have exclusively served as co-chairs for the committee since 2012. In a past year when there was not a woman in the keynote/plenary line-up, our attendees took notice and called it out specifically on the post-event evaluation and via social media. Because we want to be sure we are creating a programme that is appealing to our members and attendees, we take notice and try to be vigilant about ensuring diversity within the programme. In other words, correcting gender disparity – especially during a time of transition – requires forethought and action. SSP's programme committee was committed to gender balance; they sought out (according to their call for proposals,) ‘a variety of viewpoints from a diverse pool of speakers’, and they actively selected sessions and speakers that reflected this diversity. The result was not just a high-quality programme but a speaker lineup that was broadly representative of our industry's demographics. As an industry, scholarly publishing employs more women than men, but fails to reflect this fact among its most senior leaders. A strong, sustainable industry is one that invests in its people and that rewards strong performers irrespective of gender or any other demographic. In closing, we hope that our fellow publishing colleagues will accept our challenges – at the personal, organizational, and industry-wide levels – in order to ensure that scholarly publishing will be able to attract and retain the talented professionals of today and tomorrow. An important note on the authors' methodology: collected data are the result of manual analysis of online conference programs and membership lists and not official or externally validated counts provided by the respective organizations analysed. As such, a small degree of error may be present (e.g., due to misinterpretation of a speaker's gender). However, we believe the margin of error to be minimal and unlikely to significantly affect the results presented. The authors gratefully acknowledge the following individuals who assisted with data collection, early peer-review, and other guidance in preparing this article: Amanda Banner, Jen Beal, Melanie Dolechek, Laurel Haak, Maeg Keane, Anna O'Brien, Susan Skomal, and Terri Teleen.
