AB  - Scholarly peer review (also known as refereeing or reviewing) is defined as the process of subjecting an author's scholarly work, research, or ideas to the scrutiny of others who are experts in the same field, before a paper describing this work is published in a journal, conference proceedings, book chapter, or as an entire book. The peer review process helps the publisher (ie, the editor-in-chief, the editorial board, or the program committee) decide whether the work should be accepted, considered acceptable with revisions, or rejected. Peer reviews improve the quality of scholarly publishing, and indirectly, the quality of the research behind it. All legitimate academic journals that publish research reports depend on peer review as a means of assuring the quality of the articles that they publish. But the process has far wider implications than that. Universities commonly view an academic's published research record as the main criterion for reaching decisions related to promotions and tenure. No matter how much they may say about the importance of teaching effectiveness, academic publishing is usually the overriding determinant for career progression. Accordingly, everything associated with the publishing process is a matter of concern for career-minded researchers. There are other issues surrounding academic publishing that researchers need to understand well, including electronic publishing and open access, and they are reported well elsewhere, but peer review remains critical in all such debates. However, whilst the process is nowhere near perfect and has many critics, it remains the primary means for determining the important issue of whether a research manuscript should be published, and it should, therefore, be made as good as it can be for the sake of the journals, as well as for the careers of their authors. Peer review is carried out by scholars who have been recognised as experts in their fields. They will normally have already published several journal and/or conference papers, thereby coming to the attention of journal editors. Being invited by a journal or conference to perform peer reviews is, therefore, a worthy achievement and a valuable milestone in an academic career. However, it is possible that few such individuals will have received much training or mentoring in the review process, particularly in niche areas of academia. Indeed, receiving and responding to reviews of their own manuscripts may have been their only formal exposure to it. However, there are many resources available that outline the review process and the major publishers and journals provide reviewing guidelines and, in some cases, provide feedback to reviewers on their performance. As scholars, we have all benefited from peer review and, therefore, we have at least a moral obligation to pay forward that favour to those following behind us in the development of their careers. Moreover, if you are good at reviewing, there is a better chance of ultimately being invited to take up an editorial role in the journal that you review for, which is another worthy achievement and valuable milestone in terms of career progression. Without wishing to prescribe too heavily a format for a standard review, the following is a checklist that we have developed over the years to help prepare a review that is as comprehensive as it can be. If reviewers follow this checklist, it is highly probable that they can be confident that their review will be to the same standard. If authors are aware of the criteria against which their work is being judged, they will be better prepared to meet those criteria. This is by no means the only checklist. You can also find published examples of guides to reviewing, including: Lee (1995); Davison, de Vreede, and Briggs (2005). Wiley, the publisher of this journal, also has its own resources for reviewers here: https://authorservices.wiley.com/Reviewers/index.html. The manuscript is sufficiently detailed to permit a reader: The manuscript treats ethical issues adequately: The references are appropriate and up to date (see also Tarafdar & Davison, 2020). When authors receive a review, there is a specific process to follow. Please remember that the reviewers are freely giving their time for your benefit. Out of respect for them, it is important that you consider their review comments carefully. In principle, you should either expect to revise the manuscript following their advice, or if you disagree with the advice, then explain your reasoning carefully. If the reviewers contradict each other, the Senior Editor should provide advice on how to respond. If that advice is absent, you should contact the Senior Editor to request it. With respect to the mechanics of reporting how you have revised the article, there are a number of steps to take that will make both your life and that of the reviewers easier. First, you should prepare a table with three columns. The left column should contain a sequence number to indicate which comment is being addressed. The middle column contains the comment from each reviewer. In the right column, next to each comment, you should describe your response to the comment. This may be in the form of some revision to the manuscript, or, if you disagree with the comment, your justification for so doing. Preparing your response in this way is a big help for the reviewer, who is unlikely to relish re-reading the manuscript looking for the changes you have made and determining how they relate to the comments in each of the reviews. If you just say, “see page 6, para 2,” or words to that effect, this will not endear yourself to the reviewer. See Table 1 below for an example of how to create this table of revision notes. To conclude, experienced reviewers and journal editors will probably agree that as a reviewer the more you put into conducting a review, the more you will get back from conducting it. Likewise, as an author, the more attention you pay to your responses to reviews, the more likely it will be that your manuscript will be published.
