AB  - Medical journals are dull; I do not think there is any doubt about that. —Richard Asher, M.D., F.R.C.P.1 In 1958, Dr. Richard Asher wrote in the British Medical Journal that “medical journals are dull.”1 Among the laundry list of offenses of the publication's format was that “their wrappings [were] so drab and difficult to remove, so the journals accumulate on our desks in inconvenient piles and roll on to the floor.” Over half a century later, we feel the medical and publishing communities have succeeded in making our distinguished journals more to our readers' liking. Much of this success has to do with our journals' growing roles on the Internet, but it was not an easy evolution. Plastic and Reconstructive Surgery's first Web site, while a major leap forward, suffered from some of the same symptoms that Asher posited were driving people away from reading journals. Using Asher's example as analogy, our first Web site itself could be considered the “wrappings” to our content; it was the hard-to-manipulate shell that left our online Journal remaining unread somewhere on our readers' computer desktops. The content was superb, as always, but our users could not access it in intuitive, easy, interactive ways, and therefore the content risked going unread. In July of 2009, PRSJournal.com officially became a member of the new, interactive, community-based Web 2.0 that arose after the dot com bust. Stagnant information on a Web page would no longer do; Web sites had to work for their users, not just sit in digital piles. As Kent Anderson, editor-in-chief of the Society for Scholarly Publishing's blog, Scholarly Kitchen, said in 2008, Web 2.0 environments do not just “shovel documents online … [they] bring people and experiences online.”2 Web 2.0 environments such as the new PRSJournal.com keep online journals from succumbing to digital “dullness.” PRSJournal.com underwent a revolutionary transformation when the site was transferred to our publisher's new LWW Journals Web Platform. Once placed on this new platform, immediate changes allowed our Web site, the journal of record, to provide end users with intuitive design and highly useful tools. These first features included a vastly improved search engine, easier-to-read articles, a system for “permalinking” our supplemental digital content and videos, collaborative devices that allow users to mail articles directly to colleagues, enhanced learning tools that enable users to download figures as PowerPoint files, and personalization tools that include the ability for each reader to build his or her own collections of articles, figures, videos, and tables. With the help of Lippincott Williams & Wilkins' Web development teams, PRSJournal.com is continuing to take advantage of and introduce new interactive and interesting Web features to enhance our readers' experiences online. Earlier this year we rolled out our Stand-Alone Video Player exclusively to house our CME video collections. Soon we will be utilizing the player to host true stand-alone videos, starting with a series of lectures and intraoperative videos from the 2010 Baker Gordon Cosmetic Symposium. We hope to bring this series of videos to you each year to provide you with a new multimedia way to improve your understanding of the most cutting edge cosmetic techniques and operations. With our growing video gallery, you will not just be able to read the Journal—you'll be able to watch it, too. Over the summer, Plastic and Reconstructive Surgery launched its blog, PRSonally Speaking, which can be found on the home page. We started our blog to share our insights, comments from our esteemed Section Editors, and need-to-know news from the Editorial Office; the blog also enables you to share your thoughts with us. PRSonally Speaking became home to lively, civil debate on hot topics and great discussions pertaining to our field. We encourage you to bookmark us, subscribe to the RSS feed, and join in the ongoing conversation with Plastic and Reconstructive Surgery. PRSonally Speaking is an excellent opportunity to have fun, get engaged, and interact with the plastic and reconstructive surgery community. This has always been the community's Journal, but with the blog, the community now provides the opportunity to communicate without submitting an article for print. Also, you may have noticed the new Article as ePUB feature, which launched in July. This is an avant-garde function that allows you to take PRSJournal.com with you in reader-friendly formats for devices, including the Barnes & Noble Nook, Sony eReaders, and the Apple iPad. For readers who want the Journal always at their fingertips without having to carry around any bound volumes, this function will be incredibly useful. In the past year, Plastic and Reconstructive Surgery has also started tweeting, so that our readers and “Twitter followers” can have another avenue to keep abreast of the Journal. Follow us at www.twitter.com/prsjournal to obtain information on free content, new additions to the video library, and other Journal news and announcements. Other new features on our Web site that are designed with you in mind include a more robust Publish Ahead of Print selection and our Quick Polls, designed to let you tell us how you feel. Coming soon, PRSJournal will be launching a second release of the LWW Journals Web Platform, giving you access to many more interactive and exciting Web features that will further enhance your Web experience. These features include the Alert Me When Cited function (Fig. 1), which will allow you to sign up for an email alert any time an article of interest is cited by any newer LWW article. In the same vein, two new features will provide a list of LWW articles that cited that article, with links where available, and a ticker that shows the total number of times each articles was cited. These features enable Journal readers to follow their topics of interest beyond PRS; our Journal is part of a larger community, and now, through these citation tools, our readers can follow an article's impact and related topics from journal to journal.Fig. 1.: The Alert Me When Cited function will allow users to sign up for email alerts any time an article of interest is cited by a newer LWW article.Another new feature that will help our readers interact with Plastic and Reconstructive Surgery content in new ways is a tab on the “Most Popular” webpart that shows the Journal's Highest Impact articles. If you enjoy seeing the “most viewed” and “most emailed” articles, then the “highest impact” articles will add a new dimension to your reading of the Journal, allowing you quick access to the Journal's highest impact articles according to the ISI Hot Papers service. Adding additional support to our e-reader presence is a new Journals@LWWiPhone app, which lets readers register and identify their interests, browse Tables of Content, read abstracts, and track their “most viewed articles.” This new app is another example of how PRS content will continue to be offered in new mediums and modes, wherever and however you want to read it. Finally, we will soon be stepping behind the camera with increasing frequency to bring you more videos, including Video Discussions and Introductions by the Editor. With our recent and upcoming Web enhancements, we are taking steps closer to offering our readers the ability to personalize Plastic and Reconstructive Surgery to their own interests. You can already build your own collections of videos, pictures, and more. With the next feature release, you'll be able to track how often your article is cited. Soon you will be able to personalize the PRS experience even further: we will provide the options and you can customize your experience to what you want to read, listen to, watch, collect, and engage. Technology should be in service to the user, not the other way around. We believe these new additions to PRSJournal.com are fully in service of our users. With these changes, we are making the PRSJournal Web site a fully immersive, highly customizable environment that will continue to enhance our readers' experience with PRS content. The days of articles simply being “shoveled” online are long gone; the Journal of record is a vibrant, dynamic, evolving Web site and can be found, as always, at www.PRSJournal.com. If you have any comments or concerns, or any new features or functions you would like to see us implement, please contact us via email, our blog, Twitter … or even a traditional letter to the editor (we still gladly accept those). Our Web site is now anything but dull; let us know how we could be even more exciting. That's what Web 2.0 is all about.
