AB  - The system of scholarly publishing was established four centuries ago to serve scholars and researchers in disseminating, registering, and archiving their works and maintaining quality control. In many ways, the twenty-first-century journals are not so different from their early predecessors, and they continue to serve these multiple functions in an effective way. As in the past, journal editors manage peer review and referee databases, and authors write in linear text and build on previous knowledge through citations and reference links. Publishers bundle articles into issues and disseminate these physical objects. Librarians continue to manage physical storage on library shelves while publishers have created vast digital PDF warehouses. However, some fundamental changes are also taking place in scholarly publishing, presenting opportunities and challenges for researchers, publishers, and librarians. One such trend is the relentless growth in the size of the research base itself. Data from the Journal Citation Report (Thomson Reuters) illustrate this growth. In 2008 there were 960 journals, publishing a total of 220 000 articles in physics and related areas. In 1998, the corresponding figures were 720 and 140 000, representing 35% and 56% growth rates, respectively. The emergence of new research areas, such as nanoscience and nanotechnology, fuels part of this growth. The largest single growth factor, however, is the volume of published research from China, the result of China becoming a world power in science. The growth in the volume of published research puts pressure on established editorial processes and peer review systems, and affects referees’ willingness to engage in peer review—one of the essential pillars of the current system. The growing number of journals (look at the number of Nature progeny compared to ten years ago!) means that it has never been a better time to be an author—There are journals of all shapes and sizes to accommodate every author's needs. For editors and publishers, it means that the competition to attract authors of best research to a journal is more intense. In contrast, library budgets have not tracked this growth in published research. The pressure has been alleviated to some extent by the creation of new pricing models, and library purchasing consortia that have effectively reduced the unit cost of information and had the added benefit of providing greater online access to more journals than ever before. (In some cases, it is not individual subscribers who are customers but whole countries, via their Ministry of Education or Research using a national funding mechanism and pricing formula.) Most obviously, the internet has had a major impact on scholarly publishing. Systems required to publish a journal are now web based. For example, the American Institute of Physics (AIP) conducts web peer review using its Peer X-Press system, and accomplishes online distribution via its journal hosting system Scitation. These systems have proven very popular with authors and readers; in 2009, Scitation delivered more than full-text downloads. While most publishers have digitized back issues of journals (back to volume one in many cases), creating huge PDF warehouses, they have done little so far to address one of the persistent desires researchers express: How do I find the information I need to do my teaching and research and keep up to date? With the growing information overabundance, it is paramount that publishers begin to address this need and deliver better value by using informatics and semantic technologies to extract meaning from the large body of research now being held in the PDF warehouses. AIP is addressing this challenge by becoming an informatics-based publisher, not just a document-centric PDF publisher. Another emerging trend around the world is that governments and other funding bodies are taking a greater interest in the outputs of research that they fund as one way to promote public access. Some funding agencies have mandated that authors must deposit articles resulting from the research they fund in an institutional or subject repository at some point after the version of record has been published in a journal. In most cases, these repositories provide access to their content with no access restrictions. The embargoes between publication in a journal and open access in a repository typically range from 6 to 12 months. Within the above context, open access continues to attract a lot of attention as a business model. Publishers such as Public Library of Science and BioMed Central are open access publishers, where the author is required to pay a fee to publish and readers can access the content of these so-called OA journals at no charge. Authors’ interests in this type of arrangement vary depending on their subject fields and willingness to pay an author fee, which ranges from $1000 to $3000 per article. While there is traction for this model in some biomedical areas, there seems to be little interest, so far, in fields such as physics and chemistry. In contrast, the more familiar business model involves libraries paying a license fee or subscription to provide access to its patrons. Thus, scholarly publishing seems to be caught between two worlds that complement each other in certain ways and contrast in others. There is a world of mass linear information overabundance, and a world of relevant knowledge discoverability, business models that focus on author side or reader side payment models; multiple versions of content sit in repositories and on journal websites, all combined with a general eastward (Asia Pacific) shift in the “center of gravity” of research. There is considerable tension between these worlds. One way forward is to enhance value starting with the understanding of the true needs of scholars and researchers and responding to those needs more effectively in the online world. This will involve more than just incremental steps or using tried and tested models that have been in place for many years. Scholarly publishing will not only involve some form of validation and quality control mechanisms but also be more closely connected to researchers’ work flows, providing information they need when and where they need it in the research process. “Flat” PDFs that publishers so efficiently produce today will not be enough. While the old world of scholarly publishing is waning, the new world is emerging slowly through innovation and collaboration and by ensuring sustainable business models.
